    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="35"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d35">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Potsdam/6–645</note>
                <head>No. 35 <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Soviet Foreign Commissar</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MVM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Molotov</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_HK1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">personal and</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-26">May 26,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: Today, during the conversation
                    between <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Marshal I. V. Stalin</persName> and Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d35fn1">
                        <p>For an account of <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName>’
                            conversation with <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName>
                            regarding a meeting of Heads of Government, see <hi rend="italic"
                                >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_28">p. 28</ref>. <persName
                                corresp="#p_CMWS1">Churchill</persName>, in a message to <persName
                                corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName> sent on the same day, May 26,
                            regarding the disposition of the German Fleet, suggested to <persName
                                corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName> that the question of the German
                            Fleet “should form part of the general discussions which ought to take
                            place between us and President <persName corresp="#p_THS1"
                                >Truman</persName> at the earliest possible date”. See <ref
                                target="#d141">document No. 141</ref>. <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2"
                                >Stalin</persName> replied to <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1"
                                >Churchill</persName> on May 27 as follows (text from <hi
                                rend="italic">
                                <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName>’s
                            Correspondence</hi>, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 360): <quote
                                rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName>, who has
                                    arrived in Moscow, on behalf of the President has suggested a
                                    meeting between the three of us in the immediate future. I think
                                    that a meeting is called for and that the most convenient place
                                    would be the vicinity of Berlin. That would probably be right
                                    politically as well.</p>
                                <p>“Have you any objections?”</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>For <persName corresp="#p_CMWS1">Churchill</persName>’s reply to this
                            message, see <ref target="#d39">document No. 39</ref>.</p>
                    </note> it was mentioned with regard to a place for the pending meeting of the
                    Heads of Government of our countries that in the message of <persName
                        corresp="#p_SMIV2">I. V. Stalin</persName> to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> the region of Berlin was spoken of. For
                    the purpose of accuracy I must tell you now that mention was made of this area
                    for a meeting not in the above mentioned message but in my answering telegram to
                    Mr. <persName corresp="#p_DJE1">Joseph Davies</persName> who, referring to his
                    conversation with the President, recently raised the question of a meeting of
                    the two heads of Government and also of a place of this meeting.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d35fn2">Copies of the <persName corresp="#p_DRK1"
                            >Davies</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>
                        correspondence referred to have not been found.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">V. <hi rend="smallcaps">Molotov</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
